Report on YOLOv26 Dataset Configuration (Meta) Files
Introduction

1. Dataset YAML File
The dataset YAML file acts as the central configuration file for training.

Information Revealed by the YAML File
a) Dataset Path
The path field specifies the root directory of the dataset.
This helps YOLO locate all dataset components.

b) Training and Validation Directories
The train and val fields define where training and validation images are stored.
These folders usually contain image files such as:
* .jpg
* .png
* .jpeg

c) Class Names
The names section maps class IDs to object labels.
This tells the model:
* Class 0 corresponds to car
* Class 1 corresponds to bus
The number of entries determines the total number of object classes.

2. Dataset Directory Structure
A YOLO dataset generally follows this structure:
dataset/
│
├── images/
│   ├── train/
│   └── val/
│
├── labels/
│   ├── train/
│   └── val/
│
└── data.yaml

3. Label Files
Each image has a corresponding text annotation file.
The .txt file contains object details.
Example Label File
0 0.512 0.431 0.245 0.300
1 0.650 0.500 0.120 0.200
Meaning of Values
Format:
<class_id> <x_center> <y_center> <width> <height>
Where:
* class_id → object category number
* x_center, y_center → center coordinates of object
* width, height → dimensions of bounding box
All coordinates are normalized between 0 and 1.

4. Importance of Meta Files
These metadata/configuration files are important because they:
* Organize datasets systematically
* Help YOLO load training and validation data
* Define object classes correctly
* Provide annotation information
* Ensure compatibility during model training
Without correct configuration files, YOLO training may fail or produce inaccurate predictions.



